                        "comment": "<a class=\"user\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"/danrogers\">Dan Rogers</a>  I couldn’t either. A letter issued by 49 former NASA employees is certainly worth our full attention (despite the fact that none of them seem to be climate specialists, and represent a small fraction of NASA faculty) - but what I find troubling is that their own position on this science isn’t backed by the slightest empirical evidence. <br> <br> I agree that NASA ought to be a non-advocacy organization - reporting only on empirical data and the consensus of the scientific community’s interpretation of that data. However, this letter seems to suggest that NASA ought to withdraw from public discourse and the peer review process on the subject. This, to me, makes very little sense. <br> <br> For a deeper analysis, I’d recommend this read: http://scholarsandrogues.com/2012/04/25/errors-shortcomings-void-nasa-climate-letter/",
