                        "comment": "<a class=\"user\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"/pranay\">Pranay Krishen</a>   Where in the letter do they suggest that \"NASA ought to withdraw from public discourse and the peer review process on the subject\"? <br> <br> In regards to your link, the article beings with a blatant lie. \"The letter requested that NASA in general and the Goddard Institute for Space Studies (GISS) in particular stop publishing the scientific conclusions about the human-driven causes of global climate disruption.\" This is simply not true.  <br> <br> The article addresses the \"first error\" by cherry picking words to quote and leaving out the word \"catastrophic\" which significantly changes the sentence.  The author then goes on to try to prove that the Earth has been in fact warming, even though that was never disputed in the letter. <br> <br> The \"second error\" is addressed with another lie.  The author says \"The second error is that only a few climate scientists have declared that they deny the science underlying human-driven climate disruption, not the “hundreds” the letter claims.\" What is the authors motive to so thoroughly twist the words of the letter? <br> <br> More of the same on the \"third error\". The author says \"The third error is the letter’s reference to “tens of thousands of other scientists” who supposedly deny climate disruption.\" The misrepresentation of the letter is just out of hand by this point. <br>",
