                        "comment": "<a class=\"user\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"/danrogers\">Dan Rogers</a>   I don’t agree with your above assessment of ‘lies’ and ‘misrepresentations’. The analysis seems fair. Unlike the letter, the opinions stated in the ‘errors’ have been backed by strong data.  <br> <br> The first error does state ‘catastrophic’. What words are being ‘twisted’ in the second error? Please provide proof that there are, in fact, \"hundreds of well-known climate scientists and tens of thousands of other scientists\" that support the viewpoint of this letter. I don’t understand where you’re going with the ’third error’…  <br> <br> To make this a productive discussion, why don’t we stop sparring over wording and sentence structures. Instead, since you seem to have a better handle on the perspective of this letter, could you please - in your own words - paraphrase what its point is?  <br> <br> Some empirical evidence would go a long way towards countering the inherent bias of the author of this letter - Chairman of PlantsNeedCO2.org - whose homepage slogans include: “Earth and its inhabitants need more, not less, CO2.” and “CO2 is Earth's greatest airborne fertilizer. Without it - No Life On Earth!”",
